    <section class="section" id="problems">
      <p class="section-kicker">Where growth starts to hurt</p>
      <h3>Start with the work that costs the most time, money, and attention.</h3>
      <p>
        Every growing business has a few jobs that quietly eat the week. They are not always obvious from the outside, but your team feels them: the repeated steps, the rework, the handoffs, the waiting, the "did anyone follow up?" moments, and the skilled people spending hours on work that should be lighter.
      </p>
      <div class="cards">
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Too much copying and pasting</strong>
          <p>Turn emails, forms, PDFs, notes, and spreadsheets into clean records your team can review instead of retyping.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Quotes take too long</strong>
          <p>Help your team collect the details, draft the first version, spot missing information, and approve the final answer.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Answers live in too many places</strong>
          <p>Give employees a faster way to find what the company already knows across documents, policies, notes, and spreadsheets.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Reports steal the morning</strong>
          <p>Pull together the same numbers, flag the weird parts, and prepare updates before someone spends hours formatting them.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Documents pile up</strong>
          <p>Summarize long files, compare versions, pull out key details, and route the important pieces to the right person.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Follow-up falls through</strong>
          <p>Help sort requests, suggest next steps, remind the right people, and keep work moving without adding more meetings.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section about-section" id="about">
      <div class="about-grid">
        <div class="about-photo-wrap">
          <img
            class="about-photo"
            src="/assets/winslow-conneen-headshot.png"
            alt="Winslow Conneen, founder of Conneen AI"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="about-copy">
          <p class="section-kicker">About Conneen AI</p>
          <h3>Built by someone who likes solving the unglamorous problems that make a business run better.</h3>
          <p>
            I'm Winslow Conneen, founder of Conneen AI. I build practical AI, software, and data tools for growing businesses that have reached the point where spreadsheets, inboxes, and manual follow-up are starting to cost real time.
          </p>
          <p>
            My goal is simple: help smaller teams use modern AI in a way that feels useful, understandable, and controlled. That usually starts with listening closely to how the work actually happens, finding the task that is putting the most weight on the team, and building a focused tool around that reality.
          </p>
          <div class="about-points" aria-label="What working with Conneen AI is like">
            <article>
              <strong>Plainspoken scoping</strong>
              <p>No need to arrive with technical requirements. We can start with the messy version of the problem.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <strong>Engineering-first delivery</strong>
              <p>The work is aimed at usable systems: assistants, automations, dashboards, internal tools, and review flows.</p>
            </article>
            <article>
              <strong>People stay central</strong>
              <p>AI should prepare, organize, and accelerate the work while your team keeps judgment and approval.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section diagnostic-section" id="diagnostic">
      <div class="diagnostic-card">
        <div>
          <p class="section-kicker">Meet Scout</p>
          <h3>Not sure where AI fits? Scout starts by asking what feels too heavy.</h3>
          <p>
            Scout is Conneen AI's workflow guide: part operations detective, part relief planner. You do not need to know the right technical words. Tell Scout where time disappears, where mistakes get expensive, and where your people are doing work a machine could prepare for them.
          </p>
        </div>
        <button class="site-button primary return-chat-trigger" type="button">Open Scout</button>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="pilots">
      <p class="section-kicker">Ways AI can remove weight</p>
      <h3>The right intervention depends on where the pressure is coming from.</h3>
      <p>
        AI is not one kind of tool. Sometimes the best move is a helper that drafts. Sometimes it is a checker, a sorter, a search tool, a reminder layer, a small internal app, or a report that updates itself. The question is not "Where can we use AI?" It is "Which task is costing us the most, and what kind of assistance would take the weight off?"
      </p>
      <div class="pilot-grid">
        <article class="pilot-card">
          <strong>Drafting support</strong>
          <p><span>Use when:</span> Your team writes the same kinds of replies, quotes, summaries, reports, or proposals again and again.</p>
          <p><span>AI can help:</span> Prepare a first version from your notes, rules, examples, and customer details.</p>
          <p><span>Human role:</span> Review, edit, approve, and add the judgment that protects the relationship.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="pilot-card">
          <strong>Sorting and triage</strong>
          <p><span>Use when:</span> Requests, emails, forms, tickets, or files arrive faster than the team can organize them.</p>
          <p><span>AI can help:</span> Label what came in, pull out key details, flag urgency, and send work to the right place.</p>
          <p><span>Human role:</span> Confirm priorities, handle exceptions, and decide what needs personal attention.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="pilot-card">
          <strong>Checking and quality control</strong>
          <p><span>Use when:</span> Mistakes are costly, reviews are repetitive, or someone has to compare the same details by hand.</p>
          <p><span>AI can help:</span> Look for missing fields, odd numbers, mismatched records, policy gaps, or likely errors.</p>
          <p><span>Human role:</span> Make the final call and teach the system what matters most.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="pilot-card">
          <strong>Company memory</strong>
          <p><span>Use when:</span> Answers live in old folders, spreadsheets, SOPs, emails, policies, or in one person's head.</p>
          <p><span>AI can help:</span> Search approved materials, answer plain-language questions, and point back to the source.</p>
          <p><span>Human role:</span> Keep the source material clean and decide what the assistant is allowed to use.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="pilot-card">
          <strong>Follow-up and coordination</strong>
          <p><span>Use when:</span> Jobs stall because someone needs to remind, schedule, assign, update, or collect the next detail.</p>
          <p><span>AI can help:</span> Suggest next steps, prepare reminders, draft updates, and keep the handoff visible.</p>
          <p><span>Human role:</span> Approve customer-facing messages and make judgment calls when plans change.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="pilot-card">
          <strong>Reporting and early warning</strong>
          <p><span>Use when:</span> The business runs on spreadsheets, weekly updates, or numbers that are noticed too late.</p>
          <p><span>AI can help:</span> Prepare summaries, highlight exceptions, explain changes, and surface what needs attention.</p>
          <p><span>Human role:</span> Interpret the signal, decide the response, and keep the business context attached.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="teams">
      <p class="section-kicker">Who this is for</p>
      <h3>For businesses big enough to feel the drag, but still close enough to the work to fix it.</h3>
      <div class="cards">
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Contractors & field service</strong>
          <p>Estimates, work orders, inspections, dispatch, customer follow-up, and the admin that grows with every new job.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Property operations</strong>
          <p>Maintenance requests, vendor coordination, tenant updates, lease details, and reports that need to stay organized.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Document-heavy teams</strong>
          <p>Long files, changing requirements, repeated reviews, and details that need a careful human eye before decisions are made.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Careful, regulated work</strong>
          <p>Human-reviewed tools for teams where privacy, traceability, and controlled access matter from the beginning.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Fisheries, wildlife, energy & geospatial</strong>
          <p>Field notes, maps, reports, forecasts, and practical decisions that depend on messy real-world information.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <strong>Small business operations</strong>
          <p>Replace fragile inbox-and-spreadsheet habits with lightweight tools that help a lean team act bigger.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="process">
      <p class="section-kicker">How we start</p>
      <h3>Find the heaviest task first. Then choose the smallest useful intervention.</h3>
      <div class="timeline">
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <span>01</span>
          <strong>Find the real cost</strong>
          <p>We look for work that burns hours, delays customers, creates rework, or keeps capable people away from higher-value decisions.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <span>02</span>
          <strong>Understand how it really works</strong>
          <p>We look at who does it, what they use, where it slows down, and where a person still needs to decide.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <span>03</span>
          <strong>Choose the intervention</strong>
          <p>We decide whether the first tool should draft, sort, check, summarize, search, remind, report, or connect existing steps.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <span>04</span>
          <strong>Build a working first version</strong>
          <p>We create a focused tool around real examples from your business, with people reviewing anything important.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="timeline-item">
          <span>05</span>
          <strong>Decide what comes next</strong>
          <p>If it saves time and earns trust, we improve it or expand it. If not, you still leave with a clearer process.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section trust-section" id="trust">
      <p class="section-kicker">Guiding principle</p>
      <h3>AI should make good people more effective, not replace their judgment.</h3>
      <p>
        This is the center of the company. The goal is not to hand your business to a black box. The goal is to remove the drag around your best people so they can spend more time on customers, decisions, service, and growth.
      </p>
      <div class="trust-list">
        <article>
          <strong>People stay in the loop</strong>
          <p>Important decisions should still be reviewed by the people who know the business.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Start with a real use case</strong>
          <p>One expensive, time-sucking task is a better starting point than a broad promise to "do AI."</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Fit the business you have</strong>
          <p>The tool should work with your team, your files, your habits, and the way work actually gets done.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <strong>Handle data with care</strong>
          <p>Privacy, access, and sensitive details should be talked through before anything gets built.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

